                    "description": "In\u0101rah brings together scholars from multiple disciplines, some of them not consulted before, to shed light (in\u0101rah) on the vague origins of Islam. Vague is the sense that, though we have very explicit traditional accounts, these accounts stem from centuries later and do not seem to tally with what little hard evidence there is.\n\nFor instance, an academic veterinarian who writes a dissertation about the Military Horse in History points out that horseshoes only emerge at the end of the 9th century. This gives a Terminus Post Quem for \"hoofs sparking fire\" (sura 100) that conflicts with the alleged time of origin of the Koran. On the other hand, an Arabic linguist repositions a single diacritical dot (permitted, because the originals had no dots), and concludes that the verse doesn't refer to horses at all - which makes the Terminus Post Quem irrelevant: the text can have originated before the end of the 9th century after all, but now with a totally different meaning.\n\nThis is the kind of observations In\u0101rah is dealing with by bringing in expertise from outside the conventional arabistic, theological, legal and anthropological fields. \n\nMeanwhile In\u0101rah has produced 6 bundles of scholarly articles. I have contributed to the third and the fourth volume:\nhttp://www.verlag-hans-schiler.de/index.php?title=Gerd-R+Puin+Karl-Heinz+Ohlig+Die+dunklen+Anf\u00e4nge&art_no=M0128\n\nAn English translation of the first volume is now available:\nThe Hidden Origins of Islam: New Research Into Its Early History, Hans Schiller Verlag, 2005 ISBN 3899301285 (German); Prometheus Books, 2008 ISBN 1591026342 (English)",
